  "prompt": "Why did Ian Mckellen have emotional breakdowns when on set on the Hobbit?",
  "response": "Sir Ian McKellen, who played the iconic role of Gandalf in *The Lord of the Rings* and *The Hobbit* trilogies, experienced emotional difficulties while filming *The Hobbit* due to the extensive use of green screen technology. During the production of *The Hobbit*, much of the filming was done on soundstages with green screens, as opposed to the extensive on-location shooting used in *The Lord of the Rings*. This change in filming style was particularly challenging for McKellen.\n\nMcKellen has openly discussed how isolating and frustrating the experience was for him. Unlike in *The Lord of the Rings*, where he was able to interact with the other actors in real-world settings, *The Hobbit* required him to perform many scenes alone in front of green screens, with his co-actors added digitally later. This meant that he often had to imagine the presence of other characters and the environments, which he found to be a very unnatural and lonely way of working.\n\nIn an interview, McKellen recounted a moment where he became overwhelmed by the situation and broke down in tears. He felt disconnected from the collaborative and immersive experience of traditional filmmaking, which had been such a significant part of his joy in acting. The emotional toll of this isolation led him to question whether he could continue with the role.\n\nDespite these challenges, McKellen pushed through and completed the films, delivering a memorable performance as Gandalf. His reflections on the experience have since highlighted the impact of modern filmmaking techniques on actors and the importance of maintaining a sense of connection and creativity in the process.",
